Context:
Silva creates a scramble but
inadvertently lands an upkick on the downed Barber. Barber points it out and
Smith calls time. The kick lands to Barber’s chin, but Smith tells her it’s only a
glancing shot. A doctor comes in to examine Barber during the break. Barber
says she’s a little dizzy but she’s ready to go. The action resumes with no point
deduction.

Cejudo gets an
eye poke and time is briefly called. Cejudo can’t quite get the takedown as the
fight resumes.

Reese has some success when under fire, and he gets a bit of unwelcome relief
when McVey drives a knee directly into his cup. Reese groans, and Tognoni
immediately calls time as McVey apologizes.

Amil looks for range with his kicks, and
Emmers blasts him with left hand at the same time Amil accidentally kicks him
in the groin. Hatley sees it and calls time, with Emmers taking about 45
seconds to recover before he starts up guns blazing.

Emmers
knees him in the gut when the two are tied up, and Amil gets away with a fence
grab.

Amil’s front kick brushes the cup before striking the body, and
Hatley signs and calls time. Hatley informs Amil to not commit any more fouls,
and after about 40 seconds, they get back to business.

Amil
falls forward and grabs the fence to keep him afloat while scrambling, and
they quickly get back up to continue trading.

Tulio squeezes on Duncan against the wire while his fingers are hooked in the
chain links, allowing him to sneakily hold Duncan until Duncan explodes to
turn him around.
Bonfim tries for a leg lock off his back, and Padilla steps all the way around it and lands several punches to the back of the head.

A calf kick from Bonfim is so
immediately effective that Brown leaps at him with his knee out, hand
extended, and his finger jams in Bonfim’s eye socket. Luckily, Bonfim takes a
few seconds to clear his vision, and they resume and stay generally out of
range until the bell sounds.

This continues, and Alencar is warned for grabbing
the fence to keep Carnelossi stuck and has her hand slapped away a few
times.

Elekana beans him on the
sides and back of the head while Christian is moving, but what are rules
anymore and how are they never enforced?
Del Valle flattens out his opponent, landing shots to the back of the head but otherwise beating Dulgarian down.

When Radtke looks to advance his position, Frunza nails him with an upkick,
and then hooks his toes in the fencing. Dean tells him to stop, and Frunza
ignores him because the rules are mere suggestions in this sport.

Wells pulls his finger in the fence to try to improve his position, and when
he tries again, Tognoni shouts him down.

Gorimbo controls with right hands as Wells tries to scramble, and Wells still
works his way to the cage and grabs the fence immediately.

Wells simply explodes back up to his feet, and
he turns Gorimbo to the fence and imposes his weight all while tugging his
fingers in the chain links illegally. That makes three, maybe four loud warnings
from Tognoni with nothing else to it

Wells grinds down elbows while closely
pressed to Gorimbo in side control, and Tognoni slaps Gorimbo’s toes out of
the fence as they are pulling on it to try to get him a better spot.

The video shows that Delija’s
finger slid into the eye socket, and no five-minute clock starts for recovery
time. Instead, Smith states that if Cortes-Acosta is able to continue, he does
have the ability to restart the fight.

Petrino lifts and slams him down, but Petersen
powers his way back up and hooks his fingers in the fence. Soares tells him to
knock it off, and he disengages but is still defending the takedown.

Petersen crashes after him to take him down, and Petrino grabs the fence to
stay afloat and is fussed at by Soares but nothing else comes of it.

Carpenter wriggles out and hooks his toes in the
fence, and Maia tugs them out so Carpenter goes back to it again.
Pinto easily mat returns him, and Diniz elbows him repeatedly in the back of the head.

Ofli stacks his man
up and turns the proper direction to get out of the lock, but he pulls on the
fence more than once to do so.

The fighters trade low kicks, and Alvarez’
brushes the cup. Luque signals he is fine, and he keeps out of range until
shooting in for a single.

Montague
breaks out of the sub without issue, and she gets pounded in the face with an
illegal upkick. She stands up and motions to Perceval, who is right on top of
the action and calls time. Montague appears not compromised, and Perceval
takes a point away and resets the action back on the feet instead of putting
Carolina on her back again.

Thicknesse fires off a
front kick that drills Musasa square in the groin, and the Congolese fighter
goes down in a heap. You can’t get kicked much harder to that spot, and
Musasa knows it and appears to dry heave once or twice. Thicknesse drops to
his knees as Perdios calls time, and Perdios knows there is nothing he can do
or say to make the agonizing pain go away. Musasa needs over a minute to
even get back to his feet,

Bedoya grabs the fence to try to stay on his feet, but
Mullarkey wrenches him down from the back and gets both hooks in

Mullarkey lifts up a knee and bangs it into
Bedoya’s cup, only for “The Machine” to completely no-sell it and they go on
as if nothing happened

Bellato unloads with power strikes, one of his winging kicks brushing the cup,
and nothing happens other than Bellato getting close enough to clinch again.

Magny’s jab bounces off the forehead, and he pushes off the face and
his finger grazes the eye. Perdios tells them to be careful, and they carry on.

Simultaneous kicks fly, and Taveras’ lands square in the
groin. Jenkins groans, but only takes 10 seconds to recover.
They get back to it, but not before clapping hands to make sure things are cool
between the two.

Taveras shoots for a takedown and pushes his foe back,
and he lifts up his knee and slams it into Jenkins’ groin. Goddard loudly calls
stop, and Jenkins drops to a crouch. Goddard issues a hard warning to Tavares,
and Jenkins takes about 45 seconds to get back to it.

Sezinando catches a knee to the cup and time is called. The fight
resumes and Sezinando shoots for a takedown against the fence.

A hard inside low kick lands for Dumas, but moments later, “The
Reaper” absorbs an audible kick to the groin from Reese. Dumas immediately
collapses to the canvas in agony and the crowd groans upon viewing the
replay. Now a doctor has come in to talk to Dumas, who remains on his knees.
He informs the doctor that, “I cannot feel my right ball.” Beltran tries to
encourage Dumas to stand up, but he says he can’t get up. After that
revelation, Beltran waves off the fight.

Suarez lands a knee to the groin, which prompts
Lemos to collapse to the floor in pain as the American completes her
takedown. Time is called so Lemos can recover. The action resumes with 2:15 to
go.

A fence
grab temporarily saves Lemos, but Suarez grounds her foe moments later.

Hernandez kicks the body. Ferreira catches and attempts to counter. He gets
poked in the eye in the process and time is called. Ferreira doesn’t need much
time to recover

Ribeiro pauses the action after a glancing blow to the cup
by Rong. They go back to work with two minutes to go, and Rong immediately
goes back to work on the lead leg of his foe.

Nueraji stands out of Crosbie’s guard and as
Crosbie moves to get up, nails him with a blatantly illegal knee to the head.
Goddard stops the action, brings the cageside physician in to consult, and
upon the determination that Crosbie is medically able to fight on, asks the
fouled fighter if he wishes to continue. Crosbie immediately responds in the
affirmative. Goddard deducts two points from Nueraji and restarts the action.

Ortega fires off
another kick, this one clattering audibly off of Sterling’s cup, but Sterling
waves off any intervention by Dean.

When he finds himself on top, Morales starts attacking
with elbows, and Cimmarusti warns Idiris for striking the back of the head.

Barbosa is warned for putting her fingers in the eyes while she smothers
Silva’s mouth, and she drops 12-to-6 elbows to the body and chest.

Godinez kicks Andrade and is poked in the eye on the way back, and
Andrade stops and gives her a second to recover when Cimmarusti does not.

Chimaev starts pounding on the side of the head, and a few
punches land to the back of the head as Goddard is paying attention.

When Chimaev steps to get to
mount, Du Plessis illegally grabs the cage to reposition himself and Goddard
admonishes him for it.

Du Plessis is warned for toes in the fence
when trying to push off the wall, and after some light knees from Chimaev,
Goddard stands them up.

Cachoeira pushes off
and pokes her opponent in the eye. Dean calls time, and Edwards takes 30
seconds to clear her vision. When they resume, both ladies lob hammers at
one another,

Smith pulls on the fence a few times to improve his position, and
Kazama turns into it to make the attempt tighter.

Walker gets his hooks in, and Cerqueira tugs his toes on
the fencing to try to improve his position. Beltran admonishes him.

Walker is in big trouble, and he goes for a double again and is
shoved to his back. Cerqueira allows him to stand back up, and he gets kneed
in the groin and unloads huge punches.

Duncan pushes
off when Anders advances, and his finger slides into the vet’s eye socket.
Smith calls time and issues the Englishman a hard warning, and Anders takes
less than 30 seconds before he is good to go.

Duncan strikes out with a low kick,
pounding into Anders’ cup and forcing another foul stoppage. Smith
recognizes it and sighs, going over to tell Duncan he has to keep it clean.

A spin kick from Duncan bangs into the cup again, and it goes
uncalled as Anders is not thrilled.

Duncan grabs the fence to put himself in a better position, and Anders knees
him in the chest and then again to the stomach.

Duncan knees him
back, and he slashes with an elbow and appears to have another knee hit or at
least graze the groin.

Hill sits up, and
Lucindo elbows her in the back of the head.

A knee from Erceg bangs into the cup, and Osbourne grimaces
and Smith tells the fouling fighter to watch it. There is no break, so Osbourne
takes it into his own hands to separate himself.

Hernandez bullies Dolidze to the wall, and Dolidze grabs the fence so tightly
that Dean has to slap his hand out.

“Fluffy” connects with a few punches, takes a left hand on the way out and lets
Dolidze turn so he can accidentally bash him in the back of the head.

Dolidze grabs the fence blatantly to try to stop a
takedown, and Hernandez still completes it as Dean is yelling at the Georgian.
Dolidze ignores him when he hits the ground and tugs on it again, and Dean is 
angry but Hernandez is beating on Dolidze so it is not as if Dolidze fouled his way to an advantageous position.

Dolidze grabs the fence, and Dean has had enough of that foolishness and
deducts one point from the Georgian

Bunes attacks with elbows
off his back, at least one landing to the back of the head, but Estevam ignores
them and stays smothering.
Bunes starts first with a jabbing front kick, and Estevam responds with one that sounds like it brushes the cup.

Hatley warns Estevam for reckless punches to
the back of the head, and “Macapa” continues to slap his foe around from
behind.

Pulyaev tries to grab the fence to stay upright,
and Tognoni is paying close attention.

Gore rakes Vieira in the eye, and
Smith warns him to knock it off.

Vieira plants a one-two on the jaw, and Gore
pushes off with his thumb that swipes the eyeball. Smith calls time, and he
issues a hard warning to the fouling fighter

Vallejos backs Silva up with a right hand,
and they toss out front kicks as Vallejos bangs into the cup.

Cornolle tries to kick off with upkicks, and even lands an illegal one as Hatley
lightly admonishes her for this.

Rebecki leans on his training partner, and Duncan grabs the fence to get a
better position
Zaleski dos Santos lands in the guard, which Magny keeps open as he uses open palm strikes to the ears and back of the head a few timesâSmith warns him for it.

Yahya works his way
back to his feet, takes an illegal knee on the chin and still manages to keep
moving.

An Aslan kick
brushes the cup, and Elekana talks to him about it and gives him a front kick
in the stomach to think about.

Elekana shoots for a single that fails almost as soon as he
grabs hold of the Turkish fighter’s leg, and front kicks from the fighters brush
the cup again. Aslan shakes his cup and they do not stop
Almeida opts to shell Buday on both sides of the head rather than going for a sub, and some of his blows land on the back of the head.

Aslan leads off with multiple low
and body kicks, one of which jams into the groin cup. Elekana frowns, and
after a few seconds of recovery time, he gets back to business, where Aslan
kicks him nearly in the same spot.

Nurmagomedov grabs the fence again with his
fingers, and Perdios swats his hand and then foot out of the links.

Nurmagomedov is warned for putting his toes in the fence to pull himself to a
more advantageous position

Mitchell hangs on, and Nurmagomedov has his toes
still hooked in the fence as Perdios has to smack his toes again to pull them
out of it.

On a second effort, Almabayev is
able to take the back upright, but he has to hook his toes in the fence to stay
balanced.

Almabayev grabs the fence,
and Herzog calls him on it and breaks them apart. Almabayev apologizes, but
he goes right after Ochoa for another takedown, this time in the open cage.

Barriault succeeds in dragging “Shara Bullet” down, but Magomedov
grabs the fence to pull himself up and is lightly chided for the infraction.

They
kick at the same time, and Barriault’s foot grazes the cup. Perdios checks on
the Russian, who is good to go

McGhee turns to put his
back against the fencing, and Yan is warned for striking to the back of his head
when McGhee tries to take the fight down.

Oliveira drives a front kick that sounds like it ricocheted off the cup, but
Phillips does not express concern and shoots in for a takedown.

Johnson parries kicks and responds with his own to the inner thigh, only for
the foot to slide up and bang into Zellhuber’s undercarriage. Zellhuber groans
and Hatley calls time, and the damaged fighter needs 30 seconds to recover.

Johnson sticks his opponent
and moves quicker than Zellhuber can land on him, and he kicks Zellhuber in
the stomach and might have landed to the groin.

After a lull, Ige tosses
out a body kick, and Freire complains that it bumped his groin. Miragliotta
calls time, and the replay show that the heel of Ige jammed the Brazilian in the
cup.

Both fighters
appear to graze the cup with kicks, and Holland rolls with a combo and dings
Rodriguez with a right hand on the forehead.

Holland uses a high guard to hold on with a
triangle choke that is more of a high guard than anything, and Rodriguez grabs
the fence to get out of it.

Holloway pushing off Poirier’s face and poking him. They high-five to get going,
and then proceed to punch one another in the face.

Poirier sits down on a right hand that just misses
the mark, and Holloway pushes off and his finger slides in the eye socket
again. Herzog calls time, and Holloway immediately apologizes. Poirier accepts
it, and they get back to it with a high-five.
